{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526717"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:25:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:25:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14152"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14152","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14152"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.11,0.14,0.34,0.28]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6835"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55838"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6835"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14152"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41384"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1291"},{"type":"tags","id":"1659"},{"type":"tags","id":"2118"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"6376"},{"type":"tags","id":"6442"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15451"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33424"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43497"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55838","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55838"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of right flank pain, fever, and dysuria. She has a history of renal transplantation four months ago. Her regular medications include tacrolimus, mycophenolate, prednisolone, trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole, and valganciclovir. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 125/min, blood pressure 100/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 26/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.9\u00b0C. She has right renal angle tenderness. Urinalysis is positive for leukocytes and nitrites. Blood tests reveal a white cell count of 19 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (4-11), C-reactive protein of 160 mg/L (\u0026lt;5) and creatinine of 100 \u00b5mol/L (45-90).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate empirical antibiotic treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous ceftriaxone","Intravenous ceftriaxone plus oral doxycycline","Intravenous ceftriaxone plus intravenous amphotericin B","Intravenous ampicillin plus intravenous gentamicin","Intravenous ampicillin plus intravenous gentamicin plus intravenous amphotericin B"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs and symptoms consistent with acute pyelonephritis in the setting of a recent renal transplant. They are septic as evidenced by hypotension, tachycardia, fever and rise in inflammatory markers. The choice of empirical antibiotic therapy in this scenario is crucial and needs to consider the patient\u0027s immunosuppressed state and the potential pathogens involved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous ampicillin plus intravenous gentamicin\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate empirical treatment in this case. This combination provides broad-spectrum coverage. Ampicillin provides coverage of most Streptococcus and Enterococcus species alongside some coverage of common gram-negative organisms, with gentamicin providing excellent gram-negative coverage including Pseudomonas Aeruginosa. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous ceftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E is less preferable given it does not cover Enterococcus species and many gram negative organisms. Covering these organisms with empirical antibiotics is important given the severity of the patient\u0027s condition and their immunosuppressed state. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous ceftriaxone plus oral doxycycline\u003C/strong\u003E also falls short in covering Enterococcus and the combination is not typically used for pyelonephritis. It is a combination often seen used in pneumonia management from a practical perspective (alternatives include IV benzylpenicillin and PO doxycycline). \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous ceftriaxone plus intravenous amphotericin B\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as empirical anti-fungal therapy is not standard practice for pyelonephritis even in transplant patients. That being said, although less common, fungal infections can occur in immunosuppressed patients, and fungal analysis can be performed if high suspicion, relevant past history, or if the patient is not improving on appropriate antibiotic therapy. The combination of \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous ampicillin plus intravenous gentamicin plus intravenous amphotericin B\u003C/strong\u003E is similarly incorrect. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to note that while empirical therapy is started immediately, urine and blood cultures should be obtained before antibiotic administration. The antibiotic regimen may need to be adjusted based on culture results and local antibiotic resistance patterns. Additionally, close monitoring of renal function is crucial, especially when using potentially nephrotoxic agents like gentamicin in a transplant recipient. In most cases, only one dose of gentamicin should be administered and subsequent antibiotic treatment should be tailored to culture results. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Renal transplant recipients are at increased risk of urinary tract infections due to immunosuppression and anatomical changes.","It is important to note that while empirical therapy is started immediately, urine and blood cultures should be obtained before antibiotic administration.","The antibiotic regimen may need to be adjusted based on culture results and local antibiotic resistance patterns.","Intravenous ampicillin plus intravenous gentamicin is the empirical antibiotic regimen of choice for pyelonephritis."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines [Internet]. Tg.org.au. 2023 [cited 2024 Sep 10]. Available at: https://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/viewTopic?topicfile=acute-pyelonephritis-adults","Graversen ME, Dalgaard LS, Jensen-Fangel S, Jespersen B, \u00d8stergaard L, S\u00f8gaard OS. Risk and outcome of pyelonephritis among renal transplant recipients. BMC Infect Dis. 2016 Jun 10;16:264. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4901406/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41384"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14152"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41384","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41384"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-18T11:57:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-17T18:59:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6835"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55838"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data